comment_text: Gosh I woke up with a plan for the day.mainly chores.med taken...tick.lymphatic massage and exercises....tick.I come across this video.I watched the whole of it with Mr Tinnitus by my side.How I wish it was subtitled.what did I learn from it, my background being in mental Health....It is to work on :who am I.whst is my sense of meaning.what is my purpose in the here and now.can I challenge myself to that purpose with the right structure and direction.dodging  external forces slowing me down.can I keep  up that motivation.when experienced trauma shatters me, how to act upon it so my ego does not become maladaptive.Imstill working at balancing my Johari's window the best I can.and looking at my consciousness level.oh I dream every night.it is tiring! The best thing I believe in here is something very little can change or improve one not always a big thing does that.An example in my work.im fully retired now at 72.There was this  26 year old guy who has been in an institution most of his life.Aggressive...heavily medicated...scary.Nothing seems to work.he was looking at a car magazine one day and we started talking about cars....A guy I employed  was previously a mechanic.so I suggested we take him him for a drive.first time ever.showing the gear, the wheel etc.We open the bonnet to show him.His eyes brightened! then got an old ford put it in a garage on the grounds with a manual...All these years we thought we were doing the best we could for him.no change but from that first drive.he became better and the aggression became non existent.medication were decreased then stopped.The point of this story is we just found just a little thing that mattered to him.to result to a better quality of life, not the management for years by our "big"multi disciplinary team.It is a matter of finding and exploring it.my 50 cents!

video_title: Atheist vs Christian vs Spiritual Thinker: The Paperclip Problem That Exposes Religion!
comment_text:
The atheist presented interesting philosophical ideas and explanations. ‚ÄúDo I know my own purpose‚Ä¶assumes there is a purpose to know,‚Äù and ‚ÄúWe‚Äôve eliminated the daily survival need which has led to this [existential] crisis‚Äù of what do we do now. Theism, or anything else, bringing positive meaning (or detriment) to an individual does not mean that it is truth. His ideas on consciousness were very interesting. 

What the ‚Äúspiritual‚Äù psychiatrist describes, (over and over yikes) as ‚Äúquantifiable,‚Äù that specific action having a neurobiological effect leading to feeling less depressed and finding meaning‚Ä¶is essentially therapy. Yes, therapy can shift your mental/physical state, and it‚Äôs lovely that he helps people, but that doesn‚Äôt answer any existential questions about why people cannot find purpose, and is that universal.

I think that Stephen presented some great examples with friends who were both feeling down. None of the guests truly answered these questions and yet they each thought that they did. 

The Christian said that meaning will be found in religion and belief in higher power. 
The psychiatrist said that meaning is found in both a higher power and after a person does therapeutic work that affects their brain. 
The atheist says that meaning was evolutionarily diminished, and this is why we are feel aimless and lost, and anything else is subjective thought, and not necessarily truth. 

I think it was absolutely brilliant to bring all three of these different viewpoints together. Even if most of it was not fascinating, all are worth hearing. Of course we can feel better with belief in a higher power, like the friend in Dubai, because then we are connected to something greater than ourselves. (Though it was still shocking to hear a person state that the subjective feeling was ‚Äúevidence‚Äù of truth. Erm, no.) Of course we can find meaning and purpose by changing our neurobiological chemistry through therapeutic action, but we also need to understand our own existence when we are intellectual. Of course we will have more time to ponder why we are here and what we should be doing when we are no longer being chased by Sabre tooth cats. I believe that this evolutionary understanding is what benefits me the most. Then they can choose to integrate therapy, spirituality, etc. Each of these viewpoints expressed are relevant to someone. 

Humans are complex, social beings with the leisure to think about their own existence. I think about my childhood and how everything was about joy in the moment, playing was paramount, and how life through my limited ancillary lens resulted in a less complicated world. As children we also are never alone at the start, nearly always spending time with other people. 

Now we are all more and more separated via technology. We spend too much time alone, in our own technology bubble. We compare ourselves to others in ways that never existed throughout history, which can lead to feeling inadequate and unfulfilled. People are struggling and suffering all over the world, which we are acutely aware of‚Ä¶and evil, for lack of a better word, conflict, impending doom, destruction of the planet, and acute fear are pervasive and normalized, extinguishing childhood ideals. 

It‚Äôs not all that complicated that existence in a modern world has lead to humans becoming more complex. We have all the information, yet there is no single answer.

video_title: Atheist vs Christian vs Spiritual Thinker: The Paperclip Problem That Exposes Religion!
comment_text: I find this an interesting discussion, but feel the premise is a bit off.  First, it would have been lovely to have included a feminine voice in the discussion.  This conversation definitely had a masculine skew, IMO. People often find purpose and meaning being on any side of a religious or spiritual position. Consider the possibility that there can be a hierarchy of meaning and purpose. Theories of developmental psychology and pediatrics often focus on purpose early in life.  As we mature we replace that purpose with learning to set appropriate goals and achievements. If we continue in that maturation we develop a deeper inner awareness that reveals a correspondingly deeper and richer sense of purpose. Modern technology with social media and gaming hacks the dopamine reward system and highjacks our evolution of purpose and reduces the lives of some people to that ascribed by the social media or games.

comment_text: 1:19:00 I think the key thing Alex misses here is the direct experience of doing something for the sake of it, and being happy. If you have such an experience, you don't have to imagine sisyphus being happy, you can understand how and why he is, eventhough he is doing something meaningless. I can explain this with the analogy of colour, if you were to talk to a blind person and describe to him what colour looks like, he wouldn't truly understand. He can only imagine what colour would like, but if his blindness were to be cured and he sees colour for the first time, he would understand it, and he would realise that the imaginations he created previously were completely off the mark. And people who do see colour would not call it a delusion, it might be, but two people can sit together and acknowledge colours when they see it, it's a shared direct experience that they can communicate. Same with an ego death, if you can experience what it's like to do something for the sake of it, and derive joy out of it, you get why sisyphus can be happy, you don't have to imagine it, and you wouldn't call it a delusion just like seeing colour isn't a delusion. Maybe it is in an absolute, capital T Truth sense, but when it comes to giving people meaning, that doesn't matter because we understand the mechanism with which it can be achieved, so it is true to us. We may never understand Truth, we do not have the perspective for it, but what can be true for us, and for others, like seeing colour matters more, and is ultimately more useful in life.

Next up i will open a barrel that i maybe shoudnt open and that is fairly controversial however the ground texts ( Bible, Tora, Quran, Veden and so on and so forth, if i didnt mention the ground texts of your religion please forgive me it doesnt mean that i dont recognise  them but i am just a lad writing this stuff straight out of my head.) of all religions were not written through this/these higher beings  and also not with them.( I am no expert in any of these texts, but i am most familiar with the bible.) That doesnt mean they dont have value to humanity it just means you have to take everything with atleast a grain of salt. With every statement that is stated your thought process should be, could there be general value in this statement in todays society or does it feel wonky or at odds with your consciousness. Religions are to be questioned since they are lead by people and most importantly by humans, humans are with fault. Dont try to give the responsibility of your life to someone else, take the responsibility yourself and dont throw everything infront of god or some human, help yourself‚Ä¶ God is not in everything, tradgedies happen and sometimes they are no ones fault, forgive and lead a better life without the grudges that eat away at you.Although this comment isnt covering all i wanted to say, i hope i was of help to you this or atleast gave you food for thought, if you have a different opinion on something i am glad to hear it, just be polite and stay human. I wish you the best. Greetings from Bavaria.

On the subject of purpose:  
I think it is essential to distinguish between a personal and a universal purpose, as the two are easily confused, even in this conversation.

The universal purpose will probably never be discovered and reminds me very much of Schr√∂dinger's cat. So this is left to the imagination and can range from our existence in the matrix as a source of energy to a random existence without any purpose.

video_title: Atheist vs Christian vs Spiritual Thinker: The Paperclip Problem That Exposes Religion!
comment_text: The quest for meaning and purpose is so strong people will often adopt a premade purpose, even if objectively there are better ones out there, rather than feel rudderless in their life. It could be following a philosophical, political, aesthetic or cultural tradition. People are going to reach for one of these premade purposes, based on who and where they are in the world and it may be locally influenced. As Alex mentions, none of these speak to the validity of each claim. I believe that in many instances, people generally don't care. The point is to have a purpose, less so the content of any particular worldview or purpose. Humans are social creatures, so meaning can simply be, being a member of a group.

comment_text:
As Ian McGilchrist explained.  The music / song is not the individual  notes or the singer. It's the whole, including the cooperation of notes the emphasis. If one note is left out, the music/ song is changed.

If we behave as notes who think we are the song, we are deluding ourselves, chasing our tails.  Eventually, we will become exhausted. The song suffers.. We will eventually realise that as a single  note, we are nothing. 

 God is the whole, the purpose,  the creator, the conductor, the beginning,  the middle, and the end. We can join the song, interact, and be part of the beautiful music / sound that the conductor intended .We make  the music all the  more beautiful because we are there, because there was always a part in it  for us and because we listened to the conductor,  studied the music. Or we can stand outside. A lonely meaningless note.

 Taking  part in the music  is always  possible. We just need to reach out and join in, believe in a whole,  in relationship and make the music  all the more beautiful  and resounding because we are there. The conductor smiles because of the relationship established.  The sharing, the trust, the sacrifice of ego. The  love.
Two are required for love.
The goal / purpose is to love the God  above all ( above power,  wealth, family, sex, your sex, a person, etc) and love your neighbour as yourself.

comment_text:
From a young age, many of us are taught a familiar narrative about what life should look like: go to school, get a good job, buy a house, build a family, and eventually retire to enjoy the fruits of your labour. It's a formula that's been passed down through generations‚Äîstructured, linear, and, for a time, widely attainable.

But in today‚Äôs world, that blueprint feels increasingly out of reach for many. Economic instability, skyrocketing living costs, shifting job markets, and the pressures of modern life have made what was once considered a standard path far less accessible. Even more, many are beginning to question whether that path was ever truly fulfilling in the first place‚Äîor if it was simply a social expectation dressed up as purpose.

The truth is, not everyone fits into that mold. Some realise early on that their aspirations lie elsewhere. For others, the realisation comes later, often after chasing the traditional path and finding it empty or unattainable. As the old narrative begins to unravel, a deeper question emerges: If not that, then what?

In the absence of a clear, universal road map, people begin to search for meaning and purpose elsewhere. For some, it‚Äôs in spirituality or religion‚Äîfinding solace and direction in faith. For others, it‚Äôs through physical pursuits like fitness or athleticism, where the body becomes a vessel for discipline and transformation. Some turn to creativity‚Äîart, music, writing‚Äîas a way to express their inner worlds. Others dive into nature, activism, community, entrepreneurship, or personal growth.

The point is, the search for meaning doesn‚Äôt follow a single path. It‚Äôs personal. And in a world where the traditional markers of success are no longer guaranteed‚Äîor even desirable for some‚Äîthis search becomes more important than ever.

What we‚Äôre seeing is not a loss of direction, but a shift. A shift from living by default to living with intention. From chasing what we‚Äôre told we should want, to discovering what truly matters to us.

Meaning isn‚Äôt something you‚Äôre handed‚Äîit‚Äôs something you create. And purpose isn‚Äôt always found in achieving a big, bold goal; sometimes it‚Äôs in the quiet commitment to living authentically, staying curious, helping others, or simply being present.

In my opinion, God is a coping mechanism that is too obvious to fall back on to search for a purpose that is not a true meaning and is told to you to believe not to find it yourself. I think i'm leaning more towards the atheist route, however for death to be such a massive part of life there has to be something after death. You cannot have bad without good, the rain without the sun. So there has to be something but god is an ideology that is not proven and a been exaggerated story told by no more a man than you are.

comment_text:
You really hit the mark here, man. Perfectly said. I think that Alex is just too used to being in "debate mode" that he just has it on in every discussion, even though its not needed at times. What he's maybe missing is that humans, or at least most humans, are not rational creatures. Our feelings often override our logic. 

And so, is it really necessary to definitively assert that we only need logical answers and solutions? I mean, ideally, yes maybe thats good. But it can only work if it we live in an idealistic utopia where the best answers can be universally taught to and understood by everyone, and everyone has the same intellectual capacity and environment to be able to accept it.

I find that in the end, best solutions always comes in spectrums and variations. Alex is on the left while Greg's on the right. And Dr K is the one who's aware of this spectrum and is more practical with his approach. Different people have different methods of living with the world.


But then, I see Alex's point. I dont think we'll evolve much as a species until we grow out of these "coping mechanisms". Because we saw what happens when world powers were motivated by these claims of objective truths (which is greg's side). 

In the end, I think Dr K's position is the most practically beneficial in finding a sense of purpose.  Maybe the difference lies in how these people value different facets of experience. Dr K sees value in subjectivity, while alex and greg only cares about what is objective.
